Predatory mites belonging to the family 
Phytoseiidae
(
Acari
: 
Mesostigmata
) are important predators that constitute 60% of the biological control market worldwide (

; 

). This family includes more than 2,700 species from 94 genera that were reported from all continents, except 
Antarctica
(

). Phytoseiid mites have been continuously studied since 1960 due to their key role in augmentative and natural biological control, especially in greenhouses but also in open fields (

). Natural or naturalized populations of phytoseiid mites adapted to local environmental conditions can effectively control the aforementioned pests (

). In contrast, commercially imported predators may interfere with natural predator populations via e.g. intraguild predation, causing pest control failures and displacement of native predators (

). In addition, certain conditions are needed for the mass rearing, marketing, introduction, release, and use of beneficial organisms. The Administration for Food Safety, Veterinary Medicine,

Gazette of the 
